<sect>History<label id="history"><p>
<sect1>mgv 4.0.0: 2000-04-12<p>
<itemize>
	<item>
		Fixed an overflow bug in the page movement handling.  You used to be
		able to kill &mgv; by holding the <em/PageUp/ or <em/PageDown/ keys
		down.  This was actually fixed in a previous release but I didn't
		have confirmation.
	</item>
	<item>
		Finally added some persistence to the various option settings.
	</item>
	<item>
		Removed the palette entries from the <em/Options/ menu, these things
		are mostly reduntant now that non-default visuals are supported.
	</item>
	<item>
		Added support for converting PDF to PostScript via an external program.
		This makes viewing PDF much nicer and will serve until a better
		solution is found.  This also means that printing PDF files should
		work without PDF support in your print spooler.  See the
		<ref name="pdfConverter" id="appres-pdfConverter"> resource for more
		information.
	</item>
	<item>
		Removed the file name and date from the status line.  These were
		mainly leftovers from ghostview and I needed the space for other
		things so they went.  The file name and date are available elsewhere
		so this is no real loss.
	</item>
	<item>
		Added help messages to the status line for the menu entries.
	</item>
	<item>
		The PostScript rendering no longer uses the standard background and
		foreground colors, it uses separate color resources.  You almost
		always want the document rendered in black on white but using
		<em/-foreground/ and <em/-background/ switches (or the corresponding
		resources) used to change the colors in the PostScript viewing window
		too.  There are separate resources (<bf/postScriptForeground/ and
		<bf/postScriptBackground/) and switches (<bf/-psfg/ and <bf/-psbg/)
		for the PostScript rendering now.
	</item>
	<item>
		Fixed the Netscape based help system to use
		<tt>openURL(url,new-window)</tt> the first time we ask for help,
		subsequent requests use just <tt>openURL(url)</tt> on the window that
		we have already created.  This way we get our own Netscape window to
		use and abuse as needed without stealing a window that is already in
		use for other purposes.  Thanks to &AlbertChinAYoung; for this
		suggestion.  Thanks also to &RichardHuveneers;, I borrowed heavily
		from his xtoolwait program for the window tracking code.
	</item>
	<item>
		Fixed the <tt/configure/ script to try and figure out which optimization
		flag to use.  The new <tt/configure/ script will try running the
		compiler with <em/-O2/, <em/-xO2/, and <em/-O/, the first switch that
		appears to work will be used.  This should fix some configuration
		problems with Sun's compiler.  The <bf/OPTFLAG/ environment variable
		can still be used to specify optimization flags if <tt/configure/
		isn't choosing the ones you want.
	</item>
	<item>
		Fixed the makefiles to get the SM and ICE libraries.  The old
		<tt/configure/ was checking for SM and ICE but the makefiles were
		not linking against them.  Thanks to the FreeBSD Porting Project and
		&BrianHandy; for telling me about this problem.
	</item>
	<item>
		The <tt/configure/ script now recognizes and handles the
		<em/--without-xpm/ and <em/--without-editres/ switches.  The
		previous <tt/configure/ recognized <em/--without-xpm/ but
		ignored it.
	</item>
	<item>
		Added some minor linking fixes for RedHat Motif 2.1 which appears to
		require the Xp library; &mgv; doesn't use Xp but we'll linking with
		it if we find it.  This solution is sub-optimal but trying to
		figure out if Motif wants Xp or not is more trouble than it is
		worth.
	</item>
	<item>
		Added the <bf/suppressWarnings/ resource so that you can suppress
		Xt warning messages.  If you get any Xt warnings, please tell me
		(&EMAIL;) about them before you suppress them.
	</item>
	<item>
		&mgv; now compiles in the splash screen XBM and XPM files.  This makes
		the executable larger but closer to being stand alone.
		You can still specify other splash screen images if you don't like
		mine.
	</item>
	<item>
		Extended the <bf/mgvMark/ action to take an optional argument.  Now you
		can mark ranges of pages with shift-mouse-button1 dragging in the
		page list.
	</item>
	<item>
		The <bf/wlHelpContext/ action (generally bound to <bf/F1/) has been
		replaced with the more sensible <bf/wlHelp/ action.  The old
		action was really dumb (forgive me, I don't know what the hell
		I was thinking) so it had to die the true death.
	</item>
	<item>
		Added the <bf/wlEnableAssertions/ resource and the
		<bf/-&lsqb;no&rsqb;asserts/ switches to enable/disable run-time
		sanity checks.  I've disabled the sanity checks by default.
	</item>
	<item>
		Added a little dialog for marking page ranges.
	</item>
	<item>
		Removed support for libhelp.  Libhelp is an old Motif HTML library
		based on Mosaic, I don't think it is being maintained any more and
		the programming interface is crufty (I sent a patch in to clean a
		few things up but I never heard back).
	</item>
</itemize>

